The South African National Roads Agency Limited (SANRAL) has announced that the long-awaited N2 road project from Viedgesville to Mthatha is now in the final design stages and that an invitation to tender for the project will be posted before the end of the year. Also Read: Abokobi Town Roads Project Implementation in Nigeria Begins This was revealed at a roundtable discussion conducted on April 12 at the Rotary Stadium in Ngangelizwe Township, Mthatha, between SANRAL and King Sabata Dalindyebo (KSD) business fraternity. The road project has an R1.1 billion budget, with 30% of the funds going to small, micro, and medium businesses (SMMEs) in the KSD Local Municipality. The project includes, among other things, the building of dual carriageways from Viedgesvile to Ultra City and a number of interchanges. A further R200 million is planned for community development initiatives connected to the N2 Viedgesville to Mthatha road project. SANRAL is also intending to build an R1.2 billion N2 road bypass, which is now in the design process and is set to begin building in 2025. Nyaniso Nelani, Executive Mayor of KSD Municipality, asked all stakeholders to collaborate to ensure that the planned road improvements become a reality. Concerning SANRAL’s transformation efforts, Thandile Makwabe, SANRAL’s southern area transformation officer, stated that the agency will continue to optimize the use of local resources on its projects, ensuring that local populations benefit. He stated that SANRAL, led by the transformation philosophy, constantly ensures transparency and equal opportunity for local community members in their initiatives. He also claimed that they would continue to guarantee that women, teenagers, persons with disabilities, and military veterans, to name a few, are fully engaged in their programs. All of this is done to guarantee that SANRAL initiatives benefit local resources and community people.